Growing up in East L.A. in the nineties, @rosieacosta dismissed spirituality and wellness as something people like her didn’t do. But after being arrested at age fifteen, she knew that only a radical change would lead her away from debilitating anxiety and self-doubt. As she puts it, yoga offered her a ladder and she began to climb.

In this episode, @benjaminwdecker and @rosieacosta discuss Rosie’s first book, You Are Radically Loved, an invitation to discover the healing power of who you truly are in body, mind and spirit. In this empowering episode, filled with both grit and grace, Ben and Rosie help make spirituality accessible to everyone and will guide you in allowing yourself to become the person you are truly meant to be. 

New episodes every Thursday! The Modern Spirituality Show available everywhere you get your podcasts. And link in bio 😇

I was just thinking about a time when I was younger, standing by a lake.

This became my journey and the heart of my book "You Are Radically Loved: A Healing Journey to Self-Love". 💖

In the gentle silence of this moment, my heart is heavy with both gratitude and sorrow…

Yesterday, we lost our special guy Kramer, our pup, our family member. He graced our lives with his presence for almost a year. In that time, he taught us more about love, resilience, and compassion than we could have ever imagined.

Despite his blindness, deafness, and dementia, (yes he was a mess) he was nothing short of a warrior, a shining beacon of strength. The day we found him on the side of the road of a busy street, our vet believed he wouldn't survive a month, but our little fighter proved everyone wrong. Each day with him was a gift, a precious addition to our lives.

To those of you who have ever taken care of special needs pups, you understand the commitment it involves. Diaper changes, cleanups, sleepless nights - they became our routine, a labor of love. But the joy and love he brought into our lives made every challenge worthwhile.

In our sorrow, we must also remember the blessing of his existence, however brief. He reminded us of the fragility of life, the importance of cherishing every moment, and the immeasurable strength that lies within each of us.

Grieving is a journey. It’s painful, it's raw, it’s real, and it takes time. But within that grief, there is room for gratitude. Gratitude for the love we shared, for the lessons he taught us, for every moment we were fortunate to spend with him. To our special guy, you have left paw prints on our hearts. Though you are no longer in our world, you are forever a part of us.

'Not the least hard thing to bear when they go from us, these quiet friends,
is that they carry away with them so many years of our lives.
Yet, if they find warmth therein, who would begrudge them those years that they have so guarded?
And whatever they take, be sure they have deserved.' - John Galsworthy

May your journey across the Rainbow Bridge be filled with endless treats, warm sunlight, and all the love you've given us. Rest in peace, dear friend. You are dearly missed💔.

Hey Friends, Question, Have you ever been at a crossroads? 

You know, that point in life where the road ahead splits into two, and you're left standing, wondering which path to choose? Well, that was me, a couple of decades ago.

I had enrolled in a yoga and meditation teacher training, not with the aim to teach, but simply to learn, to grow, to explore the layers of my being. But somewhere along the way, I discovered a calling that was louder than my fears, stronger than my self-doubt.

I realized that teaching was my path forward, even though the very thought of it filled me with anxiety. I was a complete nervous wreck, questioning whether I was good enough. Then, something shifted within me, and I understood that all great teachers had to start somewhere. They too, had to conquer their fears and step into the unknown.

And so, I chose courage over comfort. I chose to embrace the opportunity to empower others, to help them see their own potential, to navigate their own paths. Because, as Jon Kabat-Zinn beautifully said, "You can't stop the waves, but you can learn to surf." 🌊

Fast forward to today, I've crafted a comprehensive 8-week Meditation Teacher Training course that's designed to help you do just that - learn to surf the waves of life with grace and resilience. It's a culmination of my journey, my experiences, my love for teaching, and the transformative power of meditation. 

Are you at a crossroad, looking to deepen your practice or considering a teaching path? I invite you to join me on this journey. Let's learn together, grow together, and surf the waves of life together. Because, my dear friends, you are, and always have been, Radically Loved. ❤️

P.S. if you are curious, you can join my free info session July 19th, 2023 at 6pm PT/ 9pm ET 🔗 link in bio. 

#RadicallyLoved #MeditationTeacherTraining #JourneyWithin #CourageOverComfort #YouAreRadicallyLoved

María Justiná Acosta Valerío 🌹 (8.9.33-8.21.23)

The indigenous spirit of my lineage pulses through me, a testament to her presence.

💔 A void has been carved in my heart. To many of you, it's no secret the profound love I held for my Abuelita. The strength of a woman who raised eight of her grandchildren alongside her own three is immeasurable.
She was the matron of my father's line.
An embodiment of grace.
The very definition of resilience.
With a will that rivaled iron.
Her favorite melody? The song of the parrot 🦜.
Whispers of birdsong transported her back to days of playful dives into the river by her childhood home.
Nature's secrets? She held them in her hands. 

The herbs, the plants, and their myriad cures. When illness struck, she was our healer, crafting tinctures from memory. And oh, her tortillas, handmade from scratch, were an expression of pure love.

Bold and sassy, she never danced around her words. If she had a thought, you'd hear it, regardless of whether you sat across the table. Yet, in the same breath, she was the pure embodiment of gentle love.

I'm at a loss for words to encapsulate her legacy. A lifetime of wisdom, of love juxtaposed with loss, of battles and her own tragic life story. Yet, above all, an indomitable spirit that taught us to persevere, to march forward.

A memory from my childhood: sitting in kindergarten, with the teacher prompting us about who loved us the most. While many murmured 'mom' or 'dad', my heart echoed 'Mi Abuelita'. The reason? "Because she makes me hot chocolate and pan dulce, and her hugs feel like heaven."

From the shanty towns of rural Guerrero, stemming from a deep indigenous lineage of earth-tenders, she often said she came from nothing. Yet, to us, she was everything.

She'd often remind me during my turbulent youth: "El que con lobos anda, a aullar se enseña”🐺. (The company you keep shapes you)

For those who've read my book, "You Are Radically Loved", you've caught glimpses of the force she was. Having been wrapped in her warmth for four decades, the thought of a world without her embrace shatters me. Yet, I remain ever grateful for the memories we've woven.

(Continued in captions ⬇️)

Seven days in Tuscany felt like I blinked and stepped into a dream. After a pause since January 2020, I was welcomed back into the embrace of retreats, and oh, how I've missed this dance. 🌻 We anchored our whole selves in a 1500s villa that whispered ancient stories, feasted on carefully curated dishes by a world-class chef, and embraced the warmth of a Pizzaiolo crafting perfect pies for our last supper, while bathing in the full moon and listening to Bad Bunny. 🍕🌕😄

Lucca's Renaissance walls held us close, its historic heartbeat echoing in our footsteps on cobblestone streets and tree-lined pathways. With each turn, Tuscany unfolded a new experience: wine tasting, a delightful cooking class, and the pure joy of just being. 🍷🍝

But the magic didn’t stop at Lucca. A day in Cinque Terra painted our view with the colors of picturesque terraces, while taking a plunge in the Mediterranean Sea 🌊. 

Every sunrise yoga class and every evening dharma talk reminded me that there's nothing quite like the energy of teaching in person.

Fun fact: Did you know Tuscany has more UNESCO World Heritage Sites than Australia or South Africa?🌟

Each moment was a page from my book, "You Are Radically Loved: A Healing Journey to Self-Love." We dived deep into mindful living, immersing our senses in the present and truly understanding radical love. 💖

For those adventureous hearts and souls seeking connection, We're unveiling TWO international retreats next year. The world is vast and waiting. Don't miss out; sign up for the newsletter for all the upcoming details. 💌✈️ Until then, stay radically loved. ❤️ #RadicallyLovedRetreat #TuscanyDreaming #mindfulliving

This passage is straight from Mark Nepo’s ‘Book of Awakening’ a cherished companion of mine for over a decade. Exactly 12 years ago today, I took a leap of faith and embarked on a journey that would forever transform my life. It all began with my very first blog, “Organic Mexican Girl,” a labor of love dedicated to reinventing my Abuelita’s Mexican recipes into vegan meals.Back then, I stood at a crossroads, feeling as though my life had hit a pause button. I was 28, yearning for something more profound. The fear of judgment and criticism nearly paralyzed me. I wavered, hesitated, and was so indecisive for what felt like an eternity.Then, these words just landed: 

“We are beautifully limited creatures, capable of great moments of full living, but we can’t have it all or experience it all. We can only, paradoxically, experience all there is by giving ourselves completely and humbly to the small path we are drawn to.” 

I hit that “Publish” button.Four years later, “Radically Loved” was born, followed by a podcast a year later, and eventually, my book five years after that. It’s been a journey of persistence and patience. Of trying new things, of failing at others, but I’ve come to realize that if you’re following your true calling, every moment is worth it. 

Anything worth having is worth waiting for.

To all of you who have been a part of this incredible journey from the beginning, thank you from the depths of my heart. 

And to those of you just joining us, welcome to the love hub. Your presence makes this journey even more beautiful. 

#RadicallyLoved

I once read a quote that said, “If I say YES to you, I say NO to me,” and I never quite resonated with it. 

Personally, I don’t believe it’s always that black and white. This topic is close to my heart because it’s something I grappled with last year…

My greatest struggle has always been my tendency to be a people-pleaser. To the extent that I’d rather become a hermit than face the world, for fear of declining an invitation or not fully engaging with someone I’d rather avoid.

In many cases, those of us who identify as people-pleasers (and if you don’t, bear with me) tend to overcommit. You could almost use “Overcommitter” and “People Pleaser” interchangeably. The bottom line is, we love helping others and would rather prioritize their needs over ours, even if it means letting ourselves down.

Research has shown that aligning our behavior with our values can lead to thriving in all aspects of our lives. It boosts our confidence, self-awareness, and mindfulness.

But how does this play out in reality? And what happens when others don’t receive our boundaries well?
